'''Critical international relations theory''' is a diverse set of schools of thought in [[international relations]] (IR) that have criticized the theoretical, meta-theoretical and/or political [[status quo]], both in IR theory and in international politics more broadly&nbsp;– from [[positivism|positivist]] as well as [[postpositivism|postpositivist]] positions. Positivist critiques include [[Marxism|Marxist]] and [[neo-Marxism|neo-Marxist]] approaches and certain ("conventional") strands of [[Constructivism in international relations|social constructivism]]. Postpositivist critiques include [[poststructuralism|poststructuralist]], [[postcolonialism|postcolonial]], "critical" [[Constructivism (international relations)|constructivist]], [[critical theory]] (in the strict sense used by the [[Frankfurt School]]), [[Neo-Gramscianism|neo-Gramscian]], most [[feminism|feminist]], and some [[English school of international relations theory|English School]] approaches, as well as non-Weberian [[historical sociology]],<ref>See, e.g., {{harvnb|Hobden|Hobson|2002}}.</ref> "[[International Political Sociology (security studies)|international political sociology]]", "[[critical geopolitics]]", and the so-called "new materialism"<ref>See, e.g., {{harvnb|van der Tuin|Dolphijn|2012}}; {{harvnb|Coole|Frost|2010}}; {{harvnb|Connolly|2013}}.</ref> (partly inspired by [[actor–network theory]]). All of these latter approaches differ from both realism and liberalism in their [[epistemology|epistemological]] and [[ontology|ontological]] premises.
Such theories are now widely recognized and taught and researched in many universities, but are less common in the United States. They are taught at both undergraduate and postgraduate levels in many major universities outside the US, where a major concern is that "a myopic discipline of IR might contribute to the continued development of a civil society in the U.S. that thinks, reflects and analyzes complex international events through a very narrow set of theoretical lenses".{{sfn|Smith|2002}}
==See also== {{Portal|International relations}} *[[Feminism (international relations)]] *[[Postcolonialism (international relations)]] *[[Postmodernism (international relations)]]
