'''DENIS-P J020529.0-115925''' is a [[star system]] in the [[constellation]] of [[Cetus]]. It is located 64 light-years (19.8 parsecs) away, based on the system's [[stellar parallax|parallax]].<ref name=Dahn2002/> It was first found in the [[Deep Near Infrared Survey of the Southern Sky]].<!-- P=Provisory or provisional designation -->

This is a triple star system containing three [[brown dwarf]]s: objects that do not have enough mass to fuse [[hydrogen]] like stars. The two brightest components, designated A and B respectively, are both [[L-type star|L-type]] objects. As of 2003, the two were separated 0.287° along a position angle of 246°.<ref name=Bouy/>

Component B was observed to elongated, suggesting a third component. This third component, named C, is a [[T-type star|T-type]] object.<ref name=Bouy/> It is separated about 1.9 [[astronomical unit]]s (au) from B, and based on a total mass of {{solar mass|0.1|link=yes}}, the two may orbit each other every 8 years.<ref name=Bouy/>

